New York NY
Sept 16 1926
Sherwood Anderson
[Toutdole] Va
Galley proofs arrived will have correction made as per your telegram.
Signed
Groff Boni A. [Liueinght]
Paid

11 Columbia Street, New York
My dear Sherwood:
I am addressing these few lines to you to [ ] you are not there. Perhaps you are in N.Y. [ ] accounts or [ ] you have been lecturing in the East, as I now attend any lecture I have not come to hear yours. But I have been reading your "[ ] " and I wonder, slightly amused, whether you still hate crowded halls filled with hopes (men and women) who want to become writers.
[ ] learning through a [ ] criticsm of American literature, I find your explanation of realism [ ] cut. Ex-futurism is not quite the right word, and I do not use 'ex futurism" for its much too much of the class- noun, and name them that, does not fit your theme, Let me call it [' '] for [ ] to point out the difference.

Dear Mr. Anderson,
Just a note in answer to your telegram.
I admire you to take the train which leave the North Station, Broston, about nine in the morning. It has parlor car accommodations and is a comparatively good train; it arrives in White River Junction, Vermont about one-fifteen.
All other trains

which you might take are wretched and I strongly urge against you coming on them.
Unless I hear of the contrary, I will meet the nine o'clock train at White River and we will drive to [ ] 
Very sincerely yours
Gail Borden

30 [ ] Avenue
80 Albans Vermont
Dear Sherwood Anderson,
Your good letter fetched me today. I am afraid that I shall be sent [ ] to Africa. Well, it doesn't matter so much. After all, I am [duftry]. Reckon I will continue [desinty]. What seems to be about all there is to this game of life. My [present] position is [ ].
---

Dear Mr. Anderson;
The address of [ ] [Bledndon] Campbell is 3 Washington Square.
With sincere wishes for the new year, [ ] 
Truly yours
[ ]
